<subSubSection id="C3404AF33E4E3C659ED9FB5FF1C0FA2A" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE519783E4E3C659ED9FB5FF6F6FACA" blockId="4.[166,1225,1226,1477]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">
D e s c r i p t i o n (by Meyer, 1933). Female 
<quantity id="4CA2B49D3E4E3C659CEAFB5FF129FB0A" box="[744,875,1226,1253]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" metricValueMax="4.7" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" unit="mm" value="41.0" valueMax="47.0" valueMin="35.0">35–47 mm</quantity>
long (or rare 68), male 
<quantity id="4CA2B49D3E4E3C659A9FFB5FF2BEFAEA" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.85" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" unit="mm" value="28.5" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="22.0">22– 35 mm</quantity>
long. Proboscis almost cylindrical, rounded in apex. Hooks by Marval (1905) in 30–32 longitudinal rows of 7–10 hooks and 5–6 spines in each row. Eggs 52–60 × 18–20.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE519783E4E3C659ED9FABFF1C0FA2A" blockId="4.[166,1225,1226,1477]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">
